05471nam a22008175i 9780231548731DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202019nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2019021927  a97802315487317 a10.7312/li--190122doi  a(DE-B1597)525837  a(OCoLC)1134394868  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aBQ4570.W6bL5 2019 4aBQ4570.W6b.L5 2020 7aREL0070102bisacsh04a294.3/44408209512231 aLi, Yuhang, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBecoming Guanyin :bArtistic Devotion of Buddhist Women in Late Imperial China /cYuhang Li. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2020] 4c©2019  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPremodern East Asia: New Horizons00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tFigures -- tIntroduction: Gendered Materialization of Guanyin -- t[ 1 ] Dancing Guanyin: The Transformative Body and Buddhist Courtesans -- t[ 2 ] Painting Guanyin with Brush and Ink: Negotiating Confucianism and Buddhism -- t[ 3 ] Embroidering Guanyin with Hair: Efficacious Pain and Skill -- t[ 4 ] Mimicking Guanyin with Hairpins: Jewelry as a Means of Transcendence -- tConclusion: From Home to Temple and Court: Restaging Women’s Devotional Objects -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe goddess Guanyin began in India as the bodhisattva Avalokiteśvara, originally a male deity. He gradually became indigenized as a female deity in China over the span of nearly a millennium. By the Ming (1358–1644) and Qing (1644–1911) periods, Guanyin had become the most popular female deity in China. In Becoming Guanyin, Yuhang Li examines how lay Buddhist women in late imperial China forged a connection with the subject of their devotion, arguing that women used their own bodies to echo that of Guanyin.Li focuses on the power of material things to enable women to access religious experience and transcendence. In particular, she examines how secular Buddhist women expressed mimetic devotion and pursued religious salvation through creative depictions of Guanyin in different media such as painting and embroidery and through bodily portrayals of the deity using jewelry and dance. These material displays expressed a worldview that differed from yet fit within the Confucian patriarchal system. Attending to the fabrication and use of “women’s things” by secular women, Li offers new insight into the relationships between worshipped and worshipper in Buddhist practice. Combining empirical research with theoretical insights from both art history and Buddhist studies, Becoming Guanyin is a field-changing analysis that reveals the interplay among material culture, religion, and their gendered transformations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aBuddhist women. 0aWomen in Buddhism. 7aRELIGION / Buddhism / History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Packagez978311064982608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook-Package Package 2019z978311066221408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2019z978311065195908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2020 Englishz978311070477808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2020z9783110704570oZDB-23-DGF40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/li--1901240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/978023154873142